<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n33094g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n33" href="#n33094g">N33 (VI.B.4)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n33all.htm#n33094g"> 94(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Gomez <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n33094g"><li>FW 545.32 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n33094g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n33094g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n33094g">MS BL 47484b-350v</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:062 <a name="rBd10" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rBd10">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd10.htm#n33094g">Draft: III&sect;3B.10</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[70ff.]</font> James Lynch Fitz-Stephen, an opulent merchant, and one of the principal inhabitants of Galway, was elected mayor in 1493; at which time a regular and friendly intercourse subsisted between the town and several parts of Spain. This mayor <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> himself went on a voyage to Spain, and was received, when at Cadiz, at the house of a rich and respected merchant, of the name of <mark>Gomez</mark>, with the utmost hospitality, and with every mark of esteem <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Upon his departure for his own country, out of a wish to make some grateful return for the numerous civilities he had recieved from the Spaniard, he requested of him, as a particular favor, to allow his son, a youth of nineteen, to accompany him to Ireland <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <font color="green">[Subsequently, out of jealousy over the attraction of a woman, Agnes, of his acquaintance to the Spaniard, Lynch&apos;s son Walter]</font> darted a poinard into <font color="green">[the Spaniard&apos;s]</font> heart, and plunged him, bleeding, into the sea. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <font color="green">[After a trial, the body having been washed ashore and discovered Walter]</font> was fully convicted of the murder, and, in public, received sentence of death from the mouth of his afflicted father, by whom he was remanded back to prison. <font color="green">[Shortly thereafter, despite the protestations of all, Lynch remained inexorable and with his own hands, on the day appointed, from an arched window that overlooked the street in which the populace was assembled, the implacable patriot]</font> launched him into eternity. <small> James Hardiman, <a name="JHHT2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JHHT2"><cite title="source">The History of the Town and County of the Town of Galway</cite></a> (1820, rpt. 1926) 73ff.</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
